================================================================
MARTIN MIDSTREAM PARTNERS L.P. (NASDAQ: MMLP)
Point of View
Fiscal Q1 2026, quarter ended March 31, 2026
(Form 10-Q, results reported April 22, 2026)
================================================================

> Top-Line Performance: Top-line softened over the past three years. Revenue was ~$790m in FY23, declined to $707.6m in FY24 (down ~(10.4%) / ~($82m) YoY), and edged up to $716.1m in FY25 (up +1.2% / +$8.5m YoY) — FY25 stability reflected Sulfur Services revenue growth of +26% (driven by the new DSM Semichem fertilizer JV ramp) with Terminalling, pure sulfur, and land transportation steady, offset by Q3 marine utilization weakness and Q4 fertilizer softness. Q1 FY26 revenue declined to $187.7m from $192.5m in Q1 FY25, down (2.5%) / ($4.8m) YoY, on fertilizer margin pressure in Sulfur Services and weaker land and marine transportation contribution.

> Profitability: Profitability deteriorated through FY25 and into Q1 FY26. For FY25, net loss widened to ($14.8m) from ($5.2m) in FY24, with Adjusted EBITDA of $99.0m vs $110.6m — MMLP reports no traditional gross margin as a midstream MLP.

In Q1 FY26, operating margin contracted to 4.3% from 7.5% in Q1 FY25, with operating income falling to $8.0m from $14.4m, driven by a $4.7m Sulfur Services Adjusted EBITDA decline (fertilizer margins on rising sulfur/ammonia input costs) and a $2.0m Transportation decline. Net loss widened to ($6.8m) from ($1.0m) as $14.0m of interest expense absorbed operating earnings; Adjusted EBITDA was $20.8m vs $27.8m.

> Cash Flows: Net cash used in operating activities was ($13.8m) in Q1 FY26, and Distributable Cash Flow was negative ($2.9m) — both funded by additional revolver draws. Total debt rose to $468.1m at March 31, 2026 from $439.1m at year-end 2025.

> Liquidity and debt position: As of March 31, 2026, liquidity under the revolving credit facility was $37.5m with minimal cash on hand. Total debt outstanding was ~$468.1m — $391.9m of 11.5% senior notes (distressed-tier coupon) plus $66.6m drawn on a now-reduced $115m revolver. Partners' capital was in deficit at ($92.7m); adjusted leverage of 5.08x sits against the new 5.50x maximum covenant, leaving only ~42 bps of headroom, and interest coverage of 1.77x sits against the new 1.65x minimum.

> Working Capital: The Q1 FY26 operating cash use of ($13.8m) was funded by additional revolver draws, leaving $37.5m of revolver availability and no meaningful cash balance — a minimal working-capital cushion outside the bank facility.

> Operational Restructuring Plan: No formal restructuring program disclosed. Management cut FY26 Adjusted EBITDA guidance to $90.0m from $96.5m on fertilizer and transportation headwinds; capex is elevated at $36.5m, driven primarily by scheduled refinery turnaround activity at the Smackover facility.

> Going Concern: No explicit "substantial doubt" statement. However, covenant headroom is razor-thin — adjusted leverage of 5.08x vs the new 5.50x maximum and interest coverage of 1.77x vs the new 1.65x minimum — with the revolver maturing November 2026 and an 11.5% senior-notes coupon consuming operating earnings.

> Related-Party & Governance Overhang: Martin Resource Management Corporation (MRMC) controls the General Partner and is the source of significant related-party revenues and operating costs. MRMC's October 2024 take-private bid for the remaining MMLP common units was terminated by mutual consent on December 26, 2024.

> Management Change: CEO Bob Bondurant has held the role since January 2021 (prior CFO from 2002); CFO is Sharon Taylor; Ruben Martin (founder's son) remains Chairman of the General Partner and President of MRMC — stable but tightly MRMC-linked leadership.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged. FY25 results on February 18, 2026 and Q1 FY26 results on April 22, 2026 were filed on schedule, with no Form 12b-25 extension reported.

